The type of cipher is unknown.

============================================================
SOLUTION
============================================================

Codeword: ILLIAD

Cipher type: Book cipher (positional index cipher)

Source text: Fermat's Latin marginal note, as reproduced in
             "Fermat's Last Theorem" by Simon Singh (1997)

Language: Spanish

============================================================
PLAINTEXT
============================================================

(raw decoded string, lowercase)
plaifairciphereselproximonivellapalabrasecretaesilliad

(with word breaks)
plaifair cipher es el proximo nivel la palabra secreta es illiad

(translated)
"Playfair cipher is the next level; the secret word is illiad"

Note: "illiad" appears with a double-L in the decoded text, which
differs from the standard English spelling "Iliad".  The double-L
reflects the character at that index position in the Latin source
text and is therefore the accepted codeword spelling.

============================================================
METHODOLOGY
============================================================

Cipher identification
---------------------
The ciphertext is a sequence of 54 small positive integers, grouped
in lines of 12 (with a final line of 6).  The largest value is 217,
which implies a source text of at least 217 characters.

The integer-sequence format, combined with the competition's thematic
connection to "Fermat's Last Theorem" by Simon Singh (mentioned in
The Code Book), strongly suggested a book cipher whose source text is
the famous Latin marginal note written by Pierre de Fermat c. 1637.

Source text identification
--------------------------
Fermat's note reads (in Latin):

  Cubem autem in duos cubos, aut quadratoquodratum in duos
  quadratoquadratos, et generaliter nullam in infinitum ultra
  quadratum potestatem in duos eiusdem nominis fas est dividere.
  Cuius rei demonstrationem mirabilem sane detexi hanc marginis
  exiguitas non careret.

(English translation: "It is impossible for a cube to be written as
a sum of two cubes, or a fourth power as a sum of two fourth powers,
or in general for any power greater than two to be written as a sum
of two like powers.  I have a truly marvellous demonstration of this
proposition which this margin is too narrow to contain.")

Decryption procedure
--------------------
1. Strip all whitespace and punctuation from the Latin text to
   produce a 225-character alphanumeric string:

   Cubemauteminduoscubosautquadratoquodratuminduos...noncareret

2. Each integer in the ciphertext is a 1-based index into this
   stripped string.  The character at that position (lowercased)
   is one letter of the plaintext.

3. Mapping all 54 indices yields the Spanish message above.

Implemented in stage05.py.

Stage 06 hint (from plaintext)
------------------------------
The plaintext reveals that stage 06 is a Playfair cipher and that
the key (shibboleth) is ILLIAD.  Stage 06 was confirmed to be a
Playfair cipher written in English, with codeword MOLYBDENUM.

